liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Clashes at the border between Israel and Lebanon's Hezbollah movement have been the deadliest since a full-blown war in 2006, with Israel ordering the evacuation of more than 20,000 residents from the border town of Kiryat Shmona on Friday. An Israeli air strike targeted three Hezbollah militants near the Lebanese border yesterday, Israel's military said. Local officials say more than 4,200 people have been displaced from villages in south Lebanon. Some 1,500 of the displaced are said to be staying in three schools in the coastal Lebanese city of Tyre, about 20 kilometres north of the border. Elsewhere, the West Bank — where Palestinians have limited self-rule under Israeli military occupation — has experienced the deadliest clashes since the second intifada uprising ended in 2005. Western countries supporting Israel fear a wider war that would open up Lebanon as a second front and the West Bank as what Israeli media call a potential third front. AP/Reuters
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: The conflict is spreading to two other fronts

An Israeli air strike targeted three Hezbollah militants near the Lebanese border yesterday, Israel's military said.
Local officials say more than 4,200 people have been displaced from villages in south Lebanon.
Some 1,500 of the displaced are said to be staying in three schools in the coastal Lebanese city of Tyre, about 20 kilometres north of the border.
